issue.title: Incorrect inlining of function with destructuring in initializer of for..of loop
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**

Bug

**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**

What the online REPL currently uses

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**

REPL defaults:

```js
{
  module: true,
  compress: {},
  mangle: {},
  output: {},
  parse: {},
  rename: {},
}
```

**`terser` input**

```js
export function caller(data, key) {
    return callee(data, key);
}

function callee(arr, key) {
    for (const { [key]: v } of arr) {
        return v;
    }
}
```

**`terser` output or error**

```ts
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}(n)}
```

**Expected result**

It should either pass `r` as second argument to the IIFE or it should not declare `r` as parameter of the inner function so that it references the variable in the outer scope. Currently `r` is always `undefined` at the destructuring

```js
// either
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}(n, r)}

// or
export function caller(n,r){return function(){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}()}
```

Note that this only seems to happen with object destructuring in for..of loops

----

There's a similar case where the reference to the default value of a destructured property is not correctly tracked.

Input: 

```js
export function caller(data, fallback) {
    return callee(data, fallback);
}

function callee(arr, fallback) {
    for (const { v = fallback} of arr) {
        return v;
    }
}
```

Output:

```js
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{v:o=r}of n)return o}(n)}
```

Same issue: `r` is always `undefined`

commits.message: mark computed properties in for..of initializers as used. Closes #1238
move AST_Scope#drop_unused into its own file

issue.title: Inlining of variables across block-scopes breaks the script
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**
Bug
**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**
5.5.1
**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**
minify()


**`terser` input**
```javascript
if(1) {
	var object = 1
	var object2 = 2
	let temp_variable= something() ? object2 : object
	{
		let object = temp_variable
		x(object)
		x(object)
	}
}
```
terser inlines `temp_variable` (default settings)

**`terser` output or error**
```javascript
{
	let object = something() ? object : object2 // throws if something() == true
	//...
}
```
Terser falsely assumed that `object` in the block-scope (declared with `let`) and outside is the same variable. 
As the conditional in the example shows, the error is not always easy to detect because an exception is thrown only on access of the uninitialized variable.

**Expected result**
```javascript
var temp_variable = something() ? object : object2
{
	let object = temp_variable
	//...
}
```
Edit: I changed the sample to be reproducible. The transform doesn't always happen like that.

issue.title: Private field not recognized inside an enclosing class
issue.body:
**Bug report**

Hello,
It seems that there's a regression when handling with private fileds introduced in version 5.16.0.
I did not encounter this problem with version 5.15.1.


**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**
terser 5.16.0

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**
npx terser my-class.js

**`terser` input**

Content of  `my-class.js` file:

    class My_class {
        #private_field = 123;

        fn() {
            const c = new (class b {})(); // <-- removing this line removes the parse error
            return this.#private_field;
        }
    }


**`terser` output or error**

    Parse error at my-class.js:6,14
                    return this.#private_field;
                                ^
    ERROR: Private field must be used in an enclosing class
        at js_error (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:554:11)
        at croak (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:1278:9)
        at subscripts (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3235:17)
        at expr_atom (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:2556:20)
        at maybe_unary (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3374:19)
        at expr_ops (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3425:24)
        at maybe_conditional (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3430:20)
        at maybe_assign (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3507:20)
        at expression (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3532:24)
        at statement (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:1491:29)


**Expected result**
(obtained with terser 5.15.1)

    class My_class{#private_field=123;fn(){const c=new class b{};return this.#private_field}}

comment.body: Try adding returning the class you want the function to return. You'll need to add the bare_returns parse option so Terser doesn't think the `return` outside a function is a syntax error.

issue.title: collapse_vars inlines variables into conflicting scopes
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**

<!-- Note: sub-optimal but correct code is NOT a bug. -->

**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)** 5.2.1 (though this bug has been present for a while)

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**

```
terser bug.js --module -c defaults=false,collapse_vars=true
```

<!-- Note: if you used the node API directly, you're expected to enable the source-map-support module such that your stack traces make sense. -->

**`terser` input**

```js
const one_name = "PASS";            
var get_one = () => {               
  if (one_name) return one_name;
};
{
  let one_name = get_one();
  console.log(one_name);
}
```

<!--
Complete valid ECMAScript code exhibiting the issue with
`terser` ALONE - without third party tools or libraries.
This means no webpack, rollup, browserify or parcel, among others.
Ideally the input should be as small as possible.
Code must be in text form - not a screen cap.
Post a link to a gist if necessary.

Issues without a reproducible test case will be closed.
-->

**`terser` output or error**

```js
const one_name = "PASS";
var get_one;

{
    let one_name = (() => {
        if (one_name) return one_name;
    })();
    console.log(one_name);
}
```

**Expected result**

`get_one` shouldn't have been inlined

## Counter example:

If the anonymous block there is replaced with a function (like below), this doesn't occur. So the code to avoid this kind of inlining is there, but it doesn't support block scopes.

```js
const one_name = "PASS";            
var get_one = () => {               
  if (one_name) return one_name;
};
leak(() => {
  let one_name = get_one();
  console.log(one_name);
})
```

    console.log(this.configs)
    console.info(this.configs)
    console.warn(this.configs)
    console.error(this.configs)
  }
```

npm run build

home-demo.e43f9d72.js
```js
printConfigs() {
    n.log("哈哈哈"),
    n.log(this.configs),
    n.info(this.configs),
    n.warn(this.configs),

vue@2.7.13

why?

  const o = [];
  for (const [t, n] of []) {
    const t = true;
    o.push(t);
  }
}
```

**Expected result**

Without conflicting consts

comment.body: Closing as the conversation on the other ticket didn't really find a bug. (for future reference, a duplicate `t` is fine in this case because the scope of `const [t` is not the same as the loop body's scope)

issue.title: drop_console option Invalid, but drop_debugger valid
issue.body:
vue.config.js
```
chainWebpack: config => {
  config.optimization.minimizer('terser').tap((args) => {
    const compress = args[0].terserOptions.compress
    compress.drop_console = true
    compress.drop_debugger = true
    return args
  })
}
```
home.vue
```
printConfigs () {
    debugger
    console.log('哈哈哈')
    console.log(this.configs)
    console.info(this.configs)
    console.warn(this.configs)
    console.error(this.configs)
  }
```

npm run build

home-demo.e43f9d72.js
```js
printConfigs() {
    n.log("哈哈哈"),
    n.log(this.configs),
    n.info(this.configs),
    n.warn(this.configs),
    n.error(this.configs)
}
```

result:
1.`debugger` keyword deleted
2.`console.*` keyword Not deleted

version:
vue@2.7.13
webpack@5.74.0
terser@5.15.1

why?

issue.title: drop_console option Invalid, but drop_debugger valid
issue.body:
vue.config.js
```
chainWebpack: config => {
  config.optimization.minimizer('terser').tap((args) => {
    const compress = args[0].terserOptions.compress
    compress.drop_console = true
    compress.drop_debugger = true
    return args
  })
}
```
home.vue
```
printConfigs () {
    debugger
    console.log('哈哈哈')
    console.log(this.configs)
    console.info(this.configs)

    console.error(this.configs)
  }
```

npm run build

home-demo.e43f9d72.js
```js
printConfigs() {
    n.log("哈哈哈"),
    n.log(this.configs),
    n.info(this.configs),
    n.warn(this.configs),
    n.error(this.configs)
}
```

result:
1.`debugger` keyword deleted
2.`console.*` keyword Not deleted

version:
vue@2.7.13
webpack@5.74.0
terser@5.15.1

why?

comment.body: `console` is here retrieved with a complex expression and reassigned by webpack, before it gets to Terser. `drop_console` only supports plain `console` references that would go to the global object. This is something that's not really possible to fix from Terser. Your only option is to get webpack to not define a `console` variable for you.

commits.message: stop using eval to create RegExps

Run Eval removing codeshift (#1171)

Remove all the places where code is built as a string and then evaled to
make a function. This improves compatability with runtimes where eval is
banned.
The codeshift does the minial set of changes to make this work, and I
have manually fixed a couple of things after running the codeshift.
* Fix the DEFNODE function for the new param order.
* Remove the map/mkshallow functions.

Fixes #925

Remove last new Function() call (#1184)

This is treated as an eval call by V8, and can't be executed in
environments where eval is blocked.

Fixes #925
allow multiple binding identifiers in `var` destructuring. Closes #1176

Switch to TraceMap for sourcemap's originalPositionFor API (#1181)

* Switch to TraceMap for sourcemap's originalPositionFor API

[trace-mapping](https://github.com/jridgewell/trace-mapping) is faster, smaller, and lighter than the `source-map` package, and doesn't require WASM, manual memory management, or async/await to use.

* Fix dependency range

* Update lib/sourcemap.js

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

garbage collect the AST while outputting code (#1189)

* garbage collect the AST while outputting code

* go through all the scopes before including source map sources in the source map

fix (domprops): add `COMPLETION_STATUS_KHR` to the domprops list (#1191)

`COMPLETION_STATUS_KHR` is a property of `KHR_parallel_shader_compile` extension of WebGLRenderingContext

See: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/KHR_parallel_shader_compile
Add note about ecma parse option being deprecated

include types export for ts4.7 nodenext resolution (#1193)

See https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/47792#issuecomment-1043819482

Switch to GenMapping for sourcemap generation (#1190)

* Switch to GenMapping for sourcemap generation

[`gen-mapping`](https://github.com/jridgewell/gen-mapping) is faster, smaller, and lighter  sourcemap generation library.

This also exposes a new `decodedMap` property on the result object. Decoded maps are free to create (it's a shallow clone of the `GenMapping` instance), and passing them to `@jridgewell/trace-mapping` is copy-free. With Babel  [recently](https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14497) adding a `decodedMap` field, a dev could pass from the Babel transpilation to Terser without any added memory use for sourcemaps.

And if there's a multi stage build process, a dev could use `@ampproject/remapping` to remap Babel, Terser, and (eg) a bundler's outputs without having to feed input maps into each stage.

* Apply suggestions from code review

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

* Fix dependency

* Switch to source-map compatible @jridgewell/source-map

This preserves API compatibility, so that loading source-map in the browser is still supported.

* Update TS types

* Support source-map's async SourceMapConsumer

* Fix sourcesContent check with source-map's SourceMapGenerator

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

comment.body:
I did some digging, and this appears to be a part of an S3 package.

Here's the commit that added all of these (control+f for it, you'll see tons of them)

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/commit/8eff0875580e30e12f2e0abd5fa402973790e697.diff

There's some compiler code in that package, that ensures all filterSensitiveLog functions are placed together at the bottom (the package is built with code generation). This is why we're seeing such repetitive code.

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/blob/33e68228fb64c53dd8f89e6be76dd5f46edc3cfd/scripts/generate-clients/code-ordering.js

The repeated variations of `(Ll||(Ll={}))` is usually how Typescript extends namespaces and other things. The `LI ||` check ensures the namespace doesn't exist, and `LI = {}` creates an empty namespace.

comment.body:
`drop_console` seems to be working properly. A common reason for options like this not to work is if your source code (or the source code from your compiler) defined a `console` variable somewhere in-scope.

```
console.log("removed")

{
  const console = window.console
  console.log("not removed")
}
```

issue.title: Enabling/disabling "compress" affects runtime performance.
issue.body:
While benchmarking and debugging a tokenizer I noticed that enabling "compress" makes our library slower.

https://github.com/csstools/postcss-plugins/commit/a53a7e309b5d1c4a9a9d63b68d2da7e01b1eeca4#diff-66687fe9558c72951548283d3141e6a1b84d232f395164788c09e088e5cfaafcR22

`compress: false`

```
-------------- csstools tokenizer -------------
tokens 37088
tokens/μs @ 95th 10.294715623293715
tokens/μs @ 50th 11.178239191387075
-----------------------------------------------
95th 3.602625012397766
90th 3.435542047023773
50th 3.3178749680519104
deviation 0.3285420536994934
```

default config :

```
-------------- csstools tokenizer -------------
tokens 37088
tokens/μs @ 95th 7.851181422159019
tokens/μs @ 50th 9.178021676167592
-----------------------------------------------
95th 4.723875045776367
90th 4.2981250286102295
50th 4.040957987308502
deviation 0.8152920007705688
```

To reproduce :

1. clone https://github.com/csstools/postcss-plugins
2. `git checkout postcss-preset-env--v8` (if it hasn't been merged yet)
3. `npm ci --no-scripts`
4. open `rollup/presets/package-typescript.mjs` (here you can remove `compress: false`)
5. `cd packages/css-tokenizer`
6. `npm run build && npm run benchmark`
7. toggle the `compress` config
8. go to `6.`

comment.body:
Assuming `bar` can be directly spread out into the loop (IE it won't end up as an IIFE) I assume it should be fine.

Question from a fellow character-by-character tokenizer maintainer: Have you tried regex-based tokenizer like https://npmjs.com/moo? I've been considering switching Terser to this to gain some maintainability, but I'm not sure if it's fundamentally slower.

I have a feeling that this is caused by inlining functions into for loops (which isn't hard to disable), but I should confirm.

comment.body:
Classes aren't inlined anymore in some cases to prevent them being created multiple times and then being !== from themselves after a compilation (eg https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/1267).

It's really tricky to analyze whether something will be executed multiple times (and specializing that for Extends), so I think this is a good trade-off for less scoping bugs, assuming it doesn't increase source code size a lot.

issue.title: How can I keep a function from being mangled?

comment.body:
I think rollup doesn't do that, as it places all modules in a large file. But I haven't checked in a while. Webpack IIUC always creates a wrapper function per module.

If it's important for some compiler or tool to pick up __ as a global function, my suggestion is to use it as a global function.

If it's not defined during development you can always import it in some module and conditionally assign it to the window object.

issue.title: How can I keep a function from being mangled?

comment.body:
The first thing to do is look at the code without minification. If there's some tool in the middle, like a bundler, it may move things around in a way that Terser won't expect.

For instance it could turn a clear `import { __ } from 'i18n'; __('abc')` into `autoGeneratedModuleObject.__('abc')`

comment.body:
I'm not even sure what the expected behavior is in the top level.

`await ( )` is clearly not an await expression, it would only be reasonable to mix it up with a function call.

But for `await + 0` or `await ( 0 )` I think Terser needs to know the context of the code it's looking at.

issue.title: Fix/issue 1124
issue.body:
fix issue #1124 

---

I fix this issue by adding a context to determine if the current expression is under the class field. if is true, then it is legal to use an `in` operator with `privatename` token. if is false. parse would throw an error.

And I find a problem is that terser allow `parse` function to accept private field even out of class field, which should be a syntax error. so I add a condition to `subscripts` function to determine if the current subscript is under class feild. if is true, parse would parse it correctly, if is false it would throw an error.

To pass the test, I delete one test from `/compress/class-properity` which allows `parse` function to accept private fields even out of class field, which should be a syntax error.

I also add a condition to binary expression, because even class field can use in operation with privatename, other expressions like add can’t use privatename without subscript. for example :
```js
// in class field
 #p in this // pass
 this.#p + 10 // pass
 input.#p + 10 // pass, input can be a param
 #p + 10 // error

```

comment.body: Thank you very much!

fix issue #1124 

---

I fix this issue by adding a context to determine if the current expression is under the class field. if is true, then it is legal to use an `in` operator with `privatename` token. if is false. parse would throw an error.

And I find a problem is that terser allow `parse` function to accept private field even out of class field, which should be a syntax error. so I add a condition to `subscripts` function to determine if the current subscript is under class feild. if is true, parse would parse it correctly, if is false it would throw an error.

To pass the test, I delete one test from `/compress/class-properity` which allows `parse` function to accept private fields even out of class field, which should be a syntax error.

I also add a condition to binary expression, because even class field can use in operation with privatename, other expressions like add can’t use privatename without subscript. for example :
```js
// in class field
 #p in this // pass
 this.#p + 10 // pass
 input.#p + 10 // pass, input can be a param
 #p + 10 // error

```

issue.title: Feature Request: Minify multiple bundles with the same mangled props context
issue.body:
Use case:

Props can be mangled by regex, i.e. by adding a trailing underscore to props to be minified and adding a regex to target.

The use case is for Electron apps or any apps which share APIs in multi-process context, which require multiple output bundles for each process. Terser allows to mangle props, the most practical approach is to apply a convention where your own props are accompanied by a trailing underscore and target it by regex. However, this is not going to work across processes / bundles and requires to be mindful about not mangling props of objects which are passed between processes - which results in an inconsistent pattern, where some props use underscores and some not.

Possibly related to https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/544 but the goal is to just ensure that different files can be minified in the same mangling context and output separately - they don't have to be taken at once. *In fact, it would even be preferable (for use with module bundlers), if this could be used separately.* I.e.

- Given a special argument, Terser would cache the mangling context and return its id
- When minifying another file, the id of the mangling context would be passed as an argument

but implementing it as a part of the previously mentioned issue would work too :)

issue.title: Incorrect inlining of function with destructuring in initializer of for..of loop
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**

Bug

**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**

What the online REPL currently uses

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**

REPL defaults:

```js
{
  module: true,
  compress: {},
  mangle: {},
  output: {},
  parse: {},
  rename: {},
}
```

**`terser` input**

```js
export function caller(data, key) {
    return callee(data, key);
}

function callee(arr, key) {
    for (const { [key]: v } of arr) {
        return v;
    }
}
```

**`terser` output or error**

```ts
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}(n)}
```

**Expected result**

It should either pass `r` as second argument to the IIFE or it should not declare `r` as parameter of the inner function so that it references the variable in the outer scope. Currently `r` is always `undefined` at the destructuring

```js
// either
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}(n, r)}

// or
export function caller(n,r){return function(){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}()}
```

Note that this only seems to happen with object destructuring in for..of loops

----

There's a similar case where the reference to the default value of a destructured property is not correctly tracked.

Input: 

```js
export function caller(data, fallback) {
    return callee(data, fallback);
}

function callee(arr, fallback) {
    for (const { v = fallback} of arr) {
        return v;
    }
}
```

Output:

```js
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{v:o=r}of n)return o}(n)}
```

Same issue: `r` is always `undefined`

commits.message: mark computed properties in for..of initializers as used. Closes #1238
move AST_Scope#drop_unused into its own file

issue.title: Inlining of variables across block-scopes breaks the script
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**
Bug
**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**
5.5.1
**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**
minify()


**`terser` input**
```javascript
if(1) {
	var object = 1
	var object2 = 2
	let temp_variable= something() ? object2 : object
	{
		let object = temp_variable
		x(object)
		x(object)
	}
}
```
terser inlines `temp_variable` (default settings)

**`terser` output or error**
```javascript
{
	let object = something() ? object : object2 // throws if something() == true
	//...
}
```
Terser falsely assumed that `object` in the block-scope (declared with `let`) and outside is the same variable. 
As the conditional in the example shows, the error is not always easy to detect because an exception is thrown only on access of the uninitialized variable.

**Expected result**
```javascript
var temp_variable = something() ? object : object2
{
	let object = temp_variable
	//...
}
```
Edit: I changed the sample to be reproducible. The transform doesn't always happen like that.

issue.title: Private field not recognized inside an enclosing class
issue.body:

Hello,
It seems that there's a regression when handling with private fileds introduced in version 5.16.0.
I did not encounter this problem with version 5.15.1.


**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**
terser 5.16.0

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**
npx terser my-class.js

**`terser` input**

Content of  `my-class.js` file:

    class My_class {
        #private_field = 123;

        fn() {
            const c = new (class b {})(); // <-- removing this line removes the parse error
            return this.#private_field;
        }
    }


**`terser` output or error**

    Parse error at my-class.js:6,14
                    return this.#private_field;
                                ^
    ERROR: Private field must be used in an enclosing class
        at js_error (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:554:11)
        at croak (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:1278:9)
        at subscripts (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3235:17)

        at maybe_unary (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3374:19)
        at expr_ops (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3425:24)
        at maybe_conditional (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3430:20)
        at maybe_assign (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3507:20)
        at expression (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:3532:24)
        at statement (C:\dev.local\ui-test\packages\atomics\node_modules\terser\dist\bundle.min.js:1491:29)


**Expected result**

issue.title: collapse_vars inlines variables into conflicting scopes
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**

<!-- Note: sub-optimal but correct code is NOT a bug. -->

**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)** 5.2.1 (though this bug has been present for a while)

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**

```
terser bug.js --module -c defaults=false,collapse_vars=true
```

<!-- Note: if you used the node API directly, you're expected to enable the source-map-support module such that your stack traces make sense. -->

**`terser` input**

```js
const one_name = "PASS";            
var get_one = () => {               
  if (one_name) return one_name;
};
{
  let one_name = get_one();
  console.log(one_name);
}
```

<!--
Complete valid ECMAScript code exhibiting the issue with
`terser` ALONE - without third party tools or libraries.
This means no webpack, rollup, browserify or parcel, among others.
Ideally the input should be as small as possible.
Code must be in text form - not a screen cap.
Post a link to a gist if necessary.

Issues without a reproducible test case will be closed.
-->

**`terser` output or error**

```js
const one_name = "PASS";
var get_one;

{
    let one_name = (() => {
        if (one_name) return one_name;
    })();
    console.log(one_name);
}
```

**Expected result**

`get_one` shouldn't have been inlined

## Counter example:

If the anonymous block there is replaced with a function (like below), this doesn't occur. So the code to avoid this kind of inlining is there, but it doesn't support block scopes.

```js
const one_name = "PASS";            
var get_one = () => {               
  if (one_name) return one_name;
};
leak(() => {
  let one_name = get_one();
  console.log(one_name);
})
```

issue.title: drop_console option Invalid, but drop_debugger valid
issue.body:
vue.config.js
```
chainWebpack: config => {
  config.optimization.minimizer('terser').tap((args) => {
    const compress = args[0].terserOptions.compress
    compress.drop_console = true
    compress.drop_debugger = true
    return args
  })
}
```
home.vue
```
printConfigs () {
    debugger
    console.log('哈哈哈')
    console.log(this.configs)
    console.info(this.configs)
    console.warn(this.configs)
    console.error(this.configs)
  }
```

npm run build

home-demo.e43f9d72.js
```js
printConfigs() {
    n.log("哈哈哈"),
    n.log(this.configs),
    n.info(this.configs),
    n.warn(this.configs),
    n.error(this.configs)
}
```

result:
1.`debugger` keyword deleted
2.`console.*` keyword Not deleted

version:
vue@2.7.13
webpack@5.74.0
terser@5.15.1

why?

comment.body: pure_funcs has the same limitation, as in, every function needs to be globally defined or Terser can't tell if it's global.

issue.body:
vue.config.js
```
chainWebpack: config => {
  config.optimization.minimizer('terser').tap((args) => {
    const compress = args[0].terserOptions.compress

```

npm run build

home-demo.e43f9d72.js
```js
printConfigs() {
    n.log("哈哈哈"),
    n.log(this.configs),
    n.info(this.configs),
    n.warn(this.configs),
    n.error(this.configs)
}
```

result:
1.`debugger` keyword deleted
2.`console.*` keyword Not deleted

version:
vue@2.7.13
webpack@5.74.0
terser@5.15.1

why?

comment.body: `console` is here retrieved with a complex expression and reassigned by webpack, before it gets to Terser. `drop_console` only supports plain `console` references that would go to the global object. This is something that's not really possible to fix from Terser. Your only option is to get webpack to not define a `console` variable for you.

commits.message: stop using eval to create RegExps

Run Eval removing codeshift (#1171)

Remove all the places where code is built as a string and then evaled to
make a function. This improves compatability with runtimes where eval is
banned.
The codeshift does the minial set of changes to make this work, and I
have manually fixed a couple of things after running the codeshift.
* Fix the DEFNODE function for the new param order.
* Remove the map/mkshallow functions.

Fixes #925

Remove last new Function() call (#1184)

This is treated as an eval call by V8, and can't be executed in
environments where eval is blocked.

Fixes #925
allow multiple binding identifiers in `var` destructuring. Closes #1176

Switch to TraceMap for sourcemap's originalPositionFor API (#1181)

* Switch to TraceMap for sourcemap's originalPositionFor API

[trace-mapping](https://github.com/jridgewell/trace-mapping) is faster, smaller, and lighter than the `source-map` package, and doesn't require WASM, manual memory management, or async/await to use.

* Fix dependency range

* Update lib/sourcemap.js

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

garbage collect the AST while outputting code (#1189)

* garbage collect the AST while outputting code

* go through all the scopes before including source map sources in the source map

fix (domprops): add `COMPLETION_STATUS_KHR` to the domprops list (#1191)

`COMPLETION_STATUS_KHR` is a property of `KHR_parallel_shader_compile` extension of WebGLRenderingContext

See: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/KHR_parallel_shader_compile
Add note about ecma parse option being deprecated

include types export for ts4.7 nodenext resolution (#1193)

See https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/47792#issuecomment-1043819482

Switch to GenMapping for sourcemap generation (#1190)

* Switch to GenMapping for sourcemap generation

[`gen-mapping`](https://github.com/jridgewell/gen-mapping) is faster, smaller, and lighter  sourcemap generation library.

This also exposes a new `decodedMap` property on the result object. Decoded maps are free to create (it's a shallow clone of the `GenMapping` instance), and passing them to `@jridgewell/trace-mapping` is copy-free. With Babel  [recently](https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14497) adding a `decodedMap` field, a dev could pass from the Babel transpilation to Terser without any added memory use for sourcemaps.

And if there's a multi stage build process, a dev could use `@ampproject/remapping` to remap Babel, Terser, and (eg) a bundler's outputs without having to feed input maps into each stage.

* Apply suggestions from code review

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

* Fix dependency

* Switch to source-map compatible @jridgewell/source-map

This preserves API compatibility, so that loading source-map in the browser is still supported.

* Update TS types

* Support source-map's async SourceMapConsumer

* Fix sourcesContent check with source-map's SourceMapGenerator

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

chore: Set permissions for GitHub actions (#1195)

* chore: Set permissions for GitHub actions

 Restrict the GitHub token permissions only to the required ones; this way, even if the attackers will succeed in compromising your workflow, they won’t be able to do much.

- Included permissions for the action. https://github.com/ossf/scorecard/blob/main/docs/checks.md#token-permissions

https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions#permissions

https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-jobs/assigning-permissions-to-jobs

[Keeping your GitHub Actions and workflows secure Part 1: Preventing pwn requests](https://securitylab.github.com/research/github-actions-preventing-pwn-requests/)

Signed-off-by: nathannaveen <42319948+nathannaveen@users.noreply.github.com>

* Update .github/workflows/ci.yml

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

Fix compressed source-maps have non-terminated segments (#1106)

This reverts commit 7c1e9cceabf445e228f28496d7af37f76129c14a.

comment.body:
I did some digging, and this appears to be a part of an S3 package.

Here's the commit that added all of these (control+f for it, you'll see tons of them)

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/commit/8eff0875580e30e12f2e0abd5fa402973790e697.diff

There's some compiler code in that package, that ensures all filterSensitiveLog functions are placed together at the bottom (the package is built with code generation). This is why we're seeing such repetitive code.

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/blob/33e68228fb64c53dd8f89e6be76dd5f46edc3cfd/scripts/generate-clients/code-ordering.js

The repeated variations of `(Ll||(Ll={}))` is usually how Typescript extends namespaces and other things. The `LI ||` check ensures the namespace doesn't exist, and `LI = {}` creates an empty namespace.

issue.title: Enabling/disabling "compress" affects runtime performance.
issue.body:
While benchmarking and debugging a tokenizer I noticed that enabling "compress" makes our library slower.

https://github.com/csstools/postcss-plugins/commit/a53a7e309b5d1c4a9a9d63b68d2da7e01b1eeca4#diff-66687fe9558c72951548283d3141e6a1b84d232f395164788c09e088e5cfaafcR22

`compress: false`

```
-------------- csstools tokenizer -------------
tokens 37088
tokens/μs @ 95th 10.294715623293715
tokens/μs @ 50th 11.178239191387075
-----------------------------------------------
95th 3.602625012397766
90th 3.435542047023773
50th 3.3178749680519104
deviation 0.3285420536994934
```

default config :

```
-------------- csstools tokenizer -------------
tokens 37088
tokens/μs @ 95th 7.851181422159019
tokens/μs @ 50th 9.178021676167592
-----------------------------------------------
95th 4.723875045776367
90th 4.2981250286102295
50th 4.040957987308502
deviation 0.8152920007705688
```

To reproduce :

1. clone https://github.com/csstools/postcss-plugins
2. `git checkout postcss-preset-env--v8` (if it hasn't been merged yet)
3. `npm ci --no-scripts`
4. open `rollup/presets/package-typescript.mjs` (here you can remove `compress: false`)
5. `cd packages/css-tokenizer`
6. `npm run build && npm run benchmark`
7. toggle the `compress` config
8. go to `6.`

comment.body:
Assuming `bar` can be directly spread out into the loop (IE it won't end up as an IIFE) I assume it should be fine.

Question from a fellow character-by-character tokenizer maintainer: Have you tried regex-based tokenizer like https://npmjs.com/moo? I've been considering switching Terser to this to gain some maintainability, but I'm not sure if it's fundamentally slower.

comment.body:
Classes aren't inlined anymore in some cases to prevent them being created multiple times and then being !== from themselves after a compilation (eg https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/1267).

It's really tricky to analyze whether something will be executed multiple times (and specializing that for Extends), so I think this is a good trade-off for less scoping bugs, assuming it doesn't increase source code size a lot.

issue.title: How can I keep a function from being mangled?

comment.body:
I think rollup doesn't do that, as it places all modules in a large file. But I haven't checked in a while. Webpack IIUC always creates a wrapper function per module.

If it's important for some compiler or tool to pick up __ as a global function, my suggestion is to use it as a global function.

If it's not defined during development you can always import it in some module and conditionally assign it to the window object.

issue.title: How can I keep a function from being mangled?

comment.body:
The first thing to do is look at the code without minification. If there's some tool in the middle, like a bundler, it may move things around in a way that Terser won't expect.

For instance it could turn a clear `import { __ } from 'i18n'; __('abc')` into `autoGeneratedModuleObject.__('abc')`

`await ( )` is clearly not an await expression, it would only be reasonable to mix it up with a function call.

issue.title: Fix/issue 1124
issue.body:
fix issue #1124 

---

I fix this issue by adding a context to determine if the current expression is under the class field. if is true, then it is legal to use an `in` operator with `privatename` token. if is false. parse would throw an error.

And I find a problem is that terser allow `parse` function to accept private field even out of class field, which should be a syntax error. so I add a condition to `subscripts` function to determine if the current subscript is under class feild. if is true, parse would parse it correctly, if is false it would throw an error.

To pass the test, I delete one test from `/compress/class-properity` which allows `parse` function to accept private fields even out of class field, which should be a syntax error.

I also add a condition to binary expression, because even class field can use in operation with privatename, other expressions like add can’t use privatename without subscript. for example :
```js
// in class field
 #p in this // pass
 this.#p + 10 // pass
 input.#p + 10 // pass, input can be a param
 #p + 10 // error

```

comment.body: Thank you very much!

issue.title: Feature Request: Minify multiple bundles with the same mangled props context
issue.body:
Use case:

Props can be mangled by regex, i.e. by adding a trailing underscore to props to be minified and adding a regex to target.

The use case is for Electron apps or any apps which share APIs in multi-process context, which require multiple output bundles for each process. Terser allows to mangle props, the most practical approach is to apply a convention where your own props are accompanied by a trailing underscore and target it by regex. However, this is not going to work across processes / bundles and requires to be mindful about not mangling props of objects which are passed between processes - which results in an inconsistent pattern, where some props use underscores and some not.

Possibly related to https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/544 but the goal is to just ensure that different files can be minified in the same mangling context and output separately - they don't have to be taken at once. *In fact, it would even be preferable (for use with module bundlers), if this could be used separately.* I.e.

- Given a special argument, Terser would cache the mangling context and return its id
- When minifying another file, the id of the mangling context would be passed as an argument

but implementing it as a part of the previously mentioned issue would work too :)

issue.title: Incorrect inlining of function with destructuring in initializer of for..of loop
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**

Bug

**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**

What the online REPL currently uses

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**

REPL defaults:

```js
{
  module: true,
  compress: {},
  mangle: {},
  output: {},
  parse: {},
  rename: {},
}
```

**`terser` input**

```js
export function caller(data, key) {
    return callee(data, key);
}

function callee(arr, key) {
    for (const { [key]: v } of arr) {
        return v;
    }
}
```

**`terser` output or error**

```ts
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}(n)}
```

**Expected result**

It should either pass `r` as second argument to the IIFE or it should not declare `r` as parameter of the inner function so that it references the variable in the outer scope. Currently `r` is always `undefined` at the destructuring

```js
// either
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}(n, r)}

// or
export function caller(n,r){return function(){for(const{[r]:o}of n)return o}()}
```

Note that this only seems to happen with object destructuring in for..of loops

----

There's a similar case where the reference to the default value of a destructured property is not correctly tracked.

Input: 

```js
export function caller(data, fallback) {
    return callee(data, fallback);
}

function callee(arr, fallback) {
    for (const { v = fallback} of arr) {
        return v;
    }
}
```

Output:

```js
export function caller(n,r){return function(n,r){for(const{v:o=r}of n)return o}(n)}
```

Same issue: `r` is always `undefined`

commits.message: mark computed properties in for..of initializers as used. Closes #1238
move AST_Scope#drop_unused into its own file

issue.title: Inlining of variables across block-scopes breaks the script
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**
Bug
**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)**
5.5.1
**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**
minify()


**`terser` input**
```javascript
if(1) {
	var object = 1
	var object2 = 2
	let temp_variable= something() ? object2 : object
	{
		let object = temp_variable
		x(object)
		x(object)
	}
}
```
terser inlines `temp_variable` (default settings)

**`terser` output or error**
```javascript
{
	let object = something() ? object : object2 // throws if something() == true
	//...
}
```
Terser falsely assumed that `object` in the block-scope (declared with `let`) and outside is the same variable. 
As the conditional in the example shows, the error is not always easy to detect because an exception is thrown only on access of the uninitialized variable.

**Expected result**
```javascript
var temp_variable = something() ? object : object2
{
	let object = temp_variable
	//...
}
```
Edit: I changed the sample to be reproducible. The transform doesn't always happen like that.

issue.title: Private field not recognized inside an enclosing class
issue.body:
**Bug report**

Hello,
It seems that there's a regression when handling with private fileds introduced in version 5.16.0.
I did not encounter this problem with version 5.15.1.

issue.title: collapse_vars inlines variables into conflicting scopes
issue.body:
<!--
Consider supporting the project!
https://opencollective.com/terser
-->

**Bug report or Feature request?**

<!-- Note: sub-optimal but correct code is NOT a bug. -->

**Version (complete output of `terser -V` or specific git commit)** 5.2.1 (though this bug has been present for a while)

**Complete CLI command or `minify()` options used**

```
terser bug.js --module -c defaults=false,collapse_vars=true
```

<!-- Note: if you used the node API directly, you're expected to enable the source-map-support module such that your stack traces make sense. -->

**`terser` input**

```js
const one_name = "PASS";            
var get_one = () => {               
  if (one_name) return one_name;
};
{
  let one_name = get_one();
  console.log(one_name);
}
```

<!--
Complete valid ECMAScript code exhibiting the issue with
`terser` ALONE - without third party tools or libraries.
This means no webpack, rollup, browserify or parcel, among others.
Ideally the input should be as small as possible.
Code must be in text form - not a screen cap.
Post a link to a gist if necessary.

Issues without a reproducible test case will be closed.
-->

**`terser` output or error**

```js
const one_name = "PASS";
var get_one;

{
    let one_name = (() => {
        if (one_name) return one_name;
    })();
    console.log(one_name);
}
```

**Expected result**

`get_one` shouldn't have been inlined

## Counter example:

If the anonymous block there is replaced with a function (like below), this doesn't occur. So the code to avoid this kind of inlining is there, but it doesn't support block scopes.

```js
const one_name = "PASS";            
var get_one = () => {               
  if (one_name) return one_name;
};
leak(() => {
  let one_name = get_one();
  console.log(one_name);
})
```

```js
printConfigs() {

    n.log(this.configs),
    n.info(this.configs),
    n.warn(this.configs),
    n.error(this.configs)
}
```

2.`console.*` keyword Not deleted

version:
vue@2.7.13
webpack@5.74.0
terser@5.15.1

why?

comment.body: `console` is here retrieved with a complex expression and reassigned by webpack, before it gets to Terser. `drop_console` only supports plain `console` references that would go to the global object. This is something that's not really possible to fix from Terser. Your only option is to get webpack to not define a `console` variable for you.

commits.message: stop using eval to create RegExps

Run Eval removing codeshift (#1171)

Remove all the places where code is built as a string and then evaled to
make a function. This improves compatability with runtimes where eval is
banned.
The codeshift does the minial set of changes to make this work, and I
have manually fixed a couple of things after running the codeshift.
* Fix the DEFNODE function for the new param order.
* Remove the map/mkshallow functions.

Fixes #925

Remove last new Function() call (#1184)

This is treated as an eval call by V8, and can't be executed in
environments where eval is blocked.

Fixes #925
allow multiple binding identifiers in `var` destructuring. Closes #1176

Switch to TraceMap for sourcemap's originalPositionFor API (#1181)

* Switch to TraceMap for sourcemap's originalPositionFor API

[trace-mapping](https://github.com/jridgewell/trace-mapping) is faster, smaller, and lighter than the `source-map` package, and doesn't require WASM, manual memory management, or async/await to use.

* Fix dependency range

* Update lib/sourcemap.js

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

garbage collect the AST while outputting code (#1189)

* garbage collect the AST while outputting code

* go through all the scopes before including source map sources in the source map

fix (domprops): add `COMPLETION_STATUS_KHR` to the domprops list (#1191)

`COMPLETION_STATUS_KHR` is a property of `KHR_parallel_shader_compile` extension of WebGLRenderingContext

See: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/KHR_parallel_shader_compile
Add note about ecma parse option being deprecated

include types export for ts4.7 nodenext resolution (#1193)

See https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/47792#issuecomment-1043819482

Switch to GenMapping for sourcemap generation (#1190)

* Switch to GenMapping for sourcemap generation

[`gen-mapping`](https://github.com/jridgewell/gen-mapping) is faster, smaller, and lighter  sourcemap generation library.

This also exposes a new `decodedMap` property on the result object. Decoded maps are free to create (it's a shallow clone of the `GenMapping` instance), and passing them to `@jridgewell/trace-mapping` is copy-free. With Babel  [recently](https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14497) adding a `decodedMap` field, a dev could pass from the Babel transpilation to Terser without any added memory use for sourcemaps.

And if there's a multi stage build process, a dev could use `@ampproject/remapping` to remap Babel, Terser, and (eg) a bundler's outputs without having to feed input maps into each stage.

* Apply suggestions from code review

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

* Fix dependency

* Switch to source-map compatible @jridgewell/source-map

This preserves API compatibility, so that loading source-map in the browser is still supported.

* Update TS types

* Support source-map's async SourceMapConsumer

* Fix sourcesContent check with source-map's SourceMapGenerator

Co-authored-by: Fábio Santos <fabiosantosart@gmail.com>

chore: Set permissions for GitHub actions (#1195)

 Restrict the GitHub token permissions only to the required ones; this way, even if the attackers will succeed in compromising your workflow, they won’t be able to do much.

https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions#permissions

https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-jobs/assigning-permissions-to-jobs

[Keeping your GitHub Actions and workflows secure Part 1: Preventing pwn requests](https://securitylab.github.com/research/github-actions-preventing-pwn-requests/)

Signed-off-by: nathannaveen <42319948+nathannaveen@users.noreply.github.com>

* Update .github/workflows/ci.yml

issue.title: Non-optimal code produced

comment.body:
I did some digging, and this appears to be a part of an S3 package.

Here's the commit that added all of these (control+f for it, you'll see tons of them)

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/commit/8eff0875580e30e12f2e0abd5fa402973790e697.diff

There's some compiler code in that package, that ensures all filterSensitiveLog functions are placed together at the bottom (the package is built with code generation). This is why we're seeing such repetitive code.

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/blob/33e68228fb64c53dd8f89e6be76dd5f46edc3cfd/scripts/generate-clients/code-ordering.js

The repeated variations of `(Ll||(Ll={}))` is usually how Typescript extends namespaces and other things. The `LI ||` check ensures the namespace doesn't exist, and `LI = {}` creates an empty namespace.

comment.body:
`drop_console` seems to be working properly. A common reason for options like this not to work is if your source code (or the source code from your compiler) defined a `console` variable somewhere in-scope.

```
console.log("removed")

{
  const console = window.console
  console.log("not removed")
}
```

issue.title: Enabling/disabling "compress" affects runtime performance.
issue.body:
While benchmarking and debugging a tokenizer I noticed that enabling "compress" makes our library slower.

https://github.com/csstools/postcss-plugins/commit/a53a7e309b5d1c4a9a9d63b68d2da7e01b1eeca4#diff-66687fe9558c72951548283d3141e6a1b84d232f395164788c09e088e5cfaafcR22

`compress: false`

```
-------------- csstools tokenizer -------------
tokens 37088
tokens/μs @ 95th 10.294715623293715
tokens/μs @ 50th 11.178239191387075
-----------------------------------------------
95th 3.602625012397766
90th 3.435542047023773
50th 3.3178749680519104
deviation 0.3285420536994934
```

default config :

```
-------------- csstools tokenizer -------------
tokens 37088
tokens/μs @ 95th 7.851181422159019
tokens/μs @ 50th 9.178021676167592
-----------------------------------------------
95th 4.723875045776367
90th 4.2981250286102295
50th 4.040957987308502
deviation 0.8152920007705688
```

To reproduce :

1. clone https://github.com/csstools/postcss-plugins
2. `git checkout postcss-preset-env--v8` (if it hasn't been merged yet)
3. `npm ci --no-scripts`
4. open `rollup/presets/package-typescript.mjs` (here you can remove `compress: false`)
5. `cd packages/css-tokenizer`
6. `npm run build && npm run benchmark`
7. toggle the `compress` config
8. go to `6.`

comment.body:
Assuming `bar` can be directly spread out into the loop (IE it won't end up as an IIFE) I assume it should be fine.

Question from a fellow character-by-character tokenizer maintainer: Have you tried regex-based tokenizer like https://npmjs.com/moo? I've been considering switching Terser to this to gain some maintainability, but I'm not sure if it's fundamentally slower.

comment.body:
Classes aren't inlined anymore in some cases to prevent them being created multiple times and then being !== from themselves after a compilation (eg https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/1267).

It's really tricky to analyze whether something will be executed multiple times (and specializing that for Extends), so I think this is a good trade-off for less scoping bugs, assuming it doesn't increase source code size a lot.

issue.title: How can I keep a function from being mangled?

comment.body:
I think rollup doesn't do that, as it places all modules in a large file. But I haven't checked in a while. Webpack IIUC always creates a wrapper function per module.

If it's important for some compiler or tool to pick up __ as a global function, my suggestion is to use it as a global function.

If it's not defined during development you can always import it in some module and conditionally assign it to the window object.

issue.title: How can I keep a function from being mangled?

comment.body:
The first thing to do is look at the code without minification. If there's some tool in the middle, like a bundler, it may move things around in a way that Terser won't expect.

For instance it could turn a clear `import { __ } from 'i18n'; __('abc')` into `autoGeneratedModuleObject.__('abc')`

<!-- Note: if you used the node API directly, you're expected to enable the source-map-support module such that your stack traces make sense. -->

comment.body:
I'm not even sure what the expected behavior is in the top level.

`await ( )` is clearly not an await expression, it would only be reasonable to mix it up with a function call.

Terser might be looking at module code, or not, and those await constructs mean different things in those contexts.

issue.title: Fix/issue 1124
issue.body:
fix issue #1124 

---

I fix this issue by adding a context to determine if the current expression is under the class field. if is true, then it is legal to use an `in` operator with `privatename` token. if is false. parse would throw an error.

And I find a problem is that terser allow `parse` function to accept private field even out of class field, which should be a syntax error. so I add a condition to `subscripts` function to determine if the current subscript is under class feild. if is true, parse would parse it correctly, if is false it would throw an error.

To pass the test, I delete one test from `/compress/class-properity` which allows `parse` function to accept private fields even out of class field, which should be a syntax error.

I also add a condition to binary expression, because even class field can use in operation with privatename, other expressions like add can’t use privatename without subscript. for example :
```js
// in class field
 #p in this // pass
 this.#p + 10 // pass
 input.#p + 10 // pass, input can be a param
 #p + 10 // error

```

comment.body: Thank you very much!

issue.title: Feature Request: Minify multiple bundles with the same mangled props context
issue.body:
Use case:

Props can be mangled by regex, i.e. by adding a trailing underscore to props to be minified and adding a regex to target.

The use case is for Electron apps or any apps which share APIs in multi-process context, which require multiple output bundles for each process. Terser allows to mangle props, the most practical approach is to apply a convention where your own props are accompanied by a trailing underscore and target it by regex. However, this is not going to work across processes / bundles and requires to be mindful about not mangling props of objects which are passed between processes - which results in an inconsistent pattern, where some props use underscores and some not.

Possibly related to https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/544 but the goal is to just ensure that different files can be minified in the same mangling context and output separately - they don't have to be taken at once. *In fact, it would even be preferable (for use with module bundlers), if this could be used separately.* I.e.

- Given a special argument, Terser would cache the mangling context and return its id
- When minifying another file, the id of the mangling context would be passed as an argument

but implementing it as a part of the previously mentioned issue would work too :)

issue.title: Feature Request: Minify multiple bundles with the same mangled props context
issue.body:
Use case:

Props can be mangled by regex, i.e. by adding a trailing underscore to props to be minified and adding a regex to target.

The use case is for Electron apps or any apps which share APIs in multi-process context, which require multiple output bundles for each process. Terser allows to mangle props, the most practical approach is to apply a convention where your own props are accompanied by a trailing underscore and target it by regex. However, this is not going to work across processes / bundles and requires to be mindful about not mangling props of objects which are passed between processes - which results in an inconsistent pattern, where some props use underscores and some not.

Possibly related to https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/544 but the goal is to just ensure that different files can be minified in the same mangling context and output separately - they don't have to be taken at once. *In fact, it would even be preferable (for use with module bundlers), if this could be used separately.* I.e.

- Given a special argument, Terser would cache the mangling context and return its id
- When minifying another file, the id of the mangling context would be passed as an argument

but implementing it as a part of the previously mentioned issue would work too :)

comment.body:
There exists a minify() option called `nameCache`, which gets mutated ( 🤮 ) and then you can use the same object again in further minification.

Look for "nameCache" under here.

https://github.com/terser/terser#api-reference
